The paper deals with spectrum sensing in cognitive radio networks, which involves signal processing and communication theory. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses the performance comparison of the proposed algorithm with other state-of-the-art methods, which falls under the category of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also involves the use of statistical methods and machine learning techniques, which can be categorized under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Finally, the paper deals with cognitive radio networks, which falls under the category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security).
